
1. What is MultiTenancy ?

 Problem Statement - Suppose we are providing ready to use RAG chatbot . NOw we have multiple clients like Netflix , Amazon .
Now each client will have their own documents which needs to be fed to vector DB . Now Each client have millions of user . 
And if suppose Amazon uploaded their Leave Policy and Netflix uploaded their Office Address And Rules . Now when user of these clients
query something , how we can make sure data should not get leaked of one client to another client . 

Ans - A single application serves multiple customers (tenants), while keeping their data logically isolated.
How RAG Creates the Risk
Document
   ↓
Chunking
   ↓
Embeddings
   ↓
Vector DB
   ↓
Retriever
   ↓
LLM

--------------------- Solution 1: Metadata Filtering (Most Common) - Store tenant information with every chunk.
Example:
{
  "chunk": "Employee leave policy...",
  "tenant_id": "client_a"
}

Another chunk:
{
  "chunk": "Quarterly revenue report...",
  "tenant_id": "client_b"
}

During retrieval:
vector_db.search(
    query_embedding,
    filter={
        "tenant_id": "client_a"
    }
)

Only Client A chunks are searched.
Architecture:

User
 ↓
JWT
 ↓
tenant_id = client_a
 ↓
Retriever
 ↓
Vector Search + Filter
 ↓
Only Client A Data
 ↓
LLM

This is how many production systems work.

------------- Solution 2: Separate Collection per Tenant
Instead of one giant collection:

vector_db
├── client_a_collection
├── client_b_collection
└── client_c_collection

When Client A queries:

collection = "client_a_collection"

Search happens only there.
Benefits:
Stronger isolation
Easier compliance

Drawback:
Thousands of tenants → thousands of collections
Operational complexity

Solution 3: Separate Database per Tenant
For enterprise customers:
Client A
   └── Dedicated Vector DB

Client B
   └── Dedicated Vector DB

Client C
   └── Dedicated Vector DB

Isolation becomes very strong.

Often used for:
Banking
Healthcare
Government

Drawback:
Expensive
Harder to manage

What About Users Inside One Client?
The interviewer may ask a follow-up:

Client A has 1000 users.
Can User1 see User2's private data?
Then you need another level of isolation.

Store:
{
  "tenant_id": "client_a",
  "user_id": "user_123"
}

Filter:
{
  "tenant_id": "client_a",
  "user_id": "user_123"
}

